{"parentUuid":"b358fd53-3f57-470b-9b26-abfaa946c4c3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a594aec0f6deff72c","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011Ccqnjxt5u6sPE1uMsH3Gc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PaNtKwEQ55RPsNej9nXZNX","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\docs\\system_architecture.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3574,"cache_read_input_tokens":68315,"output_tokens":173,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3574},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":173,"cache_read_input_tokens":68315,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3574,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3574,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcqnjwksPBhcqx5UCGH5C","attributionAgent":"documentation","type":"assistant","uuid":"e3b57c3d-b02a-4469-9dc4-23bf68de205c","timestamp":"2026-07-09T03:40:26.465Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"e3b57c3d-b02a-4469-9dc4-23bf68de205c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ab5f8963-cf84-4410-bcde-8011a87d1e73","agentId":"a594aec0f6deff72c","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PaNtKwEQ55RPsNej9nXZNX","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Meterly — system architecture\n2\t\n3\t## Overview\n4\t\n5\tMeterly ingests metered usage events, serves aggregated per-customer/metric\n6\tcounters, and enforces admin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps\n7\t(\"quotas\"). Three authenticated HTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL database, one\n8\tRedis rate-limit store, running as a Docker container on ECS Fargate behind an ALB.\n9\t\n10\t```\n11\tClient --HTTPS+API key--> ALB --> FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\n12\t                                     |-- Tier-1 (IP) / Tier-2 (api_key_id) throttle --> Redis\n13\t                                     |-- bound-parameter SQL, RLS-scoped -------------> RDS PostgreSQL\n14\t                                     |-- DB credential fetch ------------------------> Secrets Manager\n15\t                                     |-- traces/logs/errors -------------------------> CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry\n16\t```\n17\t\n18\t## Request flow — `POST /v1/events`\n19\t\n20\t1. Request-id/trace assigned, security headers queued (`src/logging/middleware.py`, `src/api/middleware.py`).\n21\t2. Tier-1 IP+route throttle (Redis token bucket; fails open on a Redis outage).\n22\t3. `require_api_key` — split-token parse, in-process verification-cache check,\n23\t   falling back to a DB lookup + Argon2id verify on a cache miss\n24\t   (`src/auth/__init__.py`, `src/auth/api_key.py`).\n25\t4. Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`).\n26\t5. Pydantic schema validation (`src/api/schemas/events.py`) — anchored\n27\t   allowlists, `extra='forbid'`.\n28\t6. `events_service.create_event` — one transaction:\n29\t   `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, and only\n30\t   if a row was inserted:\n31\t   - the quota check: `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` locks the caller's\n32\t     quota row for `(customer, metric)` (if one exists) and reads the\n33\t     current-window rollup total fresh; if `R + Q > L` the service raises\n34\t     `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`, `Retry-After` to the next\n35\t     hour boundary), which propagates out of the transaction and rolls back\n36\t     the event insert — no partial write, no rollup increment\n37\t     (`src/services/events_service.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n38\t   - otherwise, `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` the `usage_rollup`\n39\t     counter (`src/repositories/events_repo.py`).\n40\t   A duplicate `idempotency_key` (replay) never reaches the quota check at\n41\t   all — only the winning-insert branch does.\n42\t7. Error-envelope boundary catches anything unhandled and returns the generic\n43\t   `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` shape (`src/api/errors.py`); `AppError`\n44\t   lets a handler attach an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that\n45\t   overrides the default status->code map, so two different 429s\n46\t   (`rate_limited` vs. `quota_exceeded`) stay distinguishable to the caller.\n47\t\n48\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage`\n49\t\n50\tSame auth/throttle/error stack; the service floors `window` to the UTC hour\n51\tand reads a single `usage_rollup` row scoped by the caller's `api_key_id`\n52\t(`src/services/usage_service.py`, `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`). A missing\n53\tbucket returns zeros with 200, never 404.\n54\t\n55\t## Request flow — `PUT /v1/quotas`\n56\t\n57\tAdmin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer, per-metric usage cap.\n58\tAuth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> an `admin`-scope assertion in the\n59\troute's composed dependency (403 `forbidden` for a non-admin key) -> schema\n60\tvalidation (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) -> `upsert_tenant_quota`, a single\n61\t`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ...\n62\tRETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted` that reports create-vs-replace in one\n63\tround-trip (201 create / 200 replace), with a `quota.upsert` audit log\n64\t(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py`,\n65\t`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n66\t\n67\t## Data model\n68\t\n69\t- `api_keys` — the tenant/credential table (migration 0001), extended with a\n70\t  `scope` column (migration 0003: `'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated).\n71\t  `secret_hash` is Argon2id; `key_id` is the public split-token lookup\n72\t  handle. `scope='admin'` is a superset scope — an admin key does everything\n73\t  an ingest key does, plus call `PUT /v1/quotas`; a tenant that wants quotas\n74\t  provisions one admin-scoped key and uses it for both.\n75\t- `events` — append-only ingest log (migration 0001). `UNIQUE (api_key_id,\n76\t  idempotency_key)` is the idempotency guarantee; RLS policy\n77\t  `events_tenant_isolation` is the application-scoping backstop.\n78\t- `usage_rollup` — derived hourly aggregate (migration 0002, expand +\n79\t  backfill from `events`). Composite PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n80\t  window_start)`; RLS policy `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation`.\n81\t- `quotas` — per-tenant, per-customer, per-metric usage caps (migration\n82\t  0003). PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`; `CHECK (limit_per_window >=\n83\t  1)`; RLS policy `quotas_tenant_isolation`. The `POST /v1/events` quota\n84\t  check takes `FOR UPDATE` on this row to serialize concurrent writers for\n85\t  the same `(customer, metric)` — see *Quota enforcement / atomicity* below.\n86\t\n87\t## Quota enforcement / atomicity\n88\t\n89\tStrict enforcement (\"usage can never exceed `L`\") is a check-then-act on a\n90\tshared counter — the classic TOCTOU. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked`\n91\t(`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) makes it race-free with a `SELECT\n92\tlimit_per_window ... FOR UPDATE` on the quota row, run **as a separate\n93\tstatement from the subsequent `usage_rollup` read**, both inside the same\n94\ttransaction as the event insert and rollup increment\n95\t(`src/services/events_service.py`).\n96\t\n97\tThis two-round-trip shape is deliberate, not incidental: PostgreSQL's `FOR\n98\tUPDATE` only guarantees a fresh re-check of the *locked* row itself when a\n99\twaiter unblocks after the lock holder commits — it does **not** force a\n100\tfresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement (e.g. a `LEFT\n101\tJOIN` to `usage_rollup`). A waiter queued before the holder committed would\n102\tevaluate that join against its own pre-wait snapshot and read a stale total,\n103\tsilently letting concurrent writers jointly exceed the cap. Splitting the\n104\tlock-acquire and the rollup-read into two statements gives the second query\n105\tits own fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot (taken *after* the lock is held),\n106\twhich does reflect everything the previous holder just committed. This was\n107\tverified empirically during implementation: a single combined\n108\t`LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` statement let every concurrent waiter read\n109\tthe same stale total and all get admitted; the two-statement version\n110\tcorrectly serializes and caps admission at `L`\n111\t(`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n112\t\n113\tUnlimited customers (no quota row) take no lock at all — the first `SELECT\n114\t... FOR UPDATE` simply matches zero rows, so the common, zero-contention\n115\tpath stays cheap (AC20 measures its added latency under load).\n116\t\n117\t## Auth\n118\t\n119\tSplit-token API keys (`mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`), Argon2id-hashed at rest.\n120\tAn in-process, TTL-bounded verification cache (keyed on the public `key_id`,\n121\tguarded by a constant-time digest comparison) avoids paying the Argon2id cost\n122\ton every request while the durable store stays Argon2id-only. See\n123\t`src/auth/__init__.py` for the full tradeoff writeup and\n124\t`scripts/seed_api_key.py` for the only key-provisioning path (no HTTP\n125\tendpoint in this build's scope; pass `--admin` to provision a `scope='admin'`\n126\tkey for `PUT /v1/quotas`, including the DAST-context admin test key, DAST-3).\n127\t\n128\t## Rate limiting\n129\t\n130\tTwo Redis token-bucket tiers (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`): Tier-1 pre-auth,\n131\tkeyed on IP+route; Tier-2 post-auth, keyed on the authenticated\n132\t`api_key_id`. Both fail open (log a warning, allow the request) on a Redis\n133\tconnection error rather than failing every request — an availability\n134\ttradeoff recorded in `.pipeline/surface-delta.md`.\n135\t\n136\t## Observability\n137\t\n138\tStructured JSON logs (structlog) to stdout -> CloudWatch, with a centralized\n139\tredaction processor (`src/logging/__init__.py`). OTel traces -> ADOT sidecar\n140\t-> X-Ray; Sentry for release-tagged error tracking with a `before_send`\n141\tPII/secret scrubber (`src/observability/`). SLO burn-rate alarms and the\n142\tminimum-three canary alarms are declared in `infra/modules/observability`.\n143\t\n144\t## Infrastructure\n145\t\n146\tTerraform under `infra/`: `modules/{network,compute,data,observability,edge}`\n147\thold the real resources; `envs/{staging,prod}/main.tf` are the two\n148\tself-contained deploy roots (own provider + backend, since Terraform only\n149\tpermits a backend configuration in a root module) that instantiate the same\n150\tmodules at different scale. See each module's file header comments for the\n151\tspecific resources and the security-baseline items they satisfy\n152\t(encryption at rest, private subnets, least-privilege IAM, no `BYPASSRLS`).\n153\t\n154\t## Known deviations / accepted risks\n155\t\n156\tSee `.pipeline/surface-delta.md` for the rate-limit fail-open behavior and the\n157\tOTel/Sentry wiring-at-construction-time change vs. the plan's original\n158\tlifespan-hook placement. See `plan.md`'s \"Open questions\" section for the\n159\taccepted risks around key-revocation latency, `api_key_id`-as-tenant-scope,\n160\tand the Postgres app-role bootstrap's CI-network-reachability prerequisite.\n161\t"}]},"uuid":"9f084ff8-b053-4e19-a80f-4f656a59108b","timestamp":"2026-07-09T03:40:26.502Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e3b57c3d-b02a-4469-9dc4-23bf68de205c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
